        // The elements $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ are the last $n$ elements.
        //
        // $M_1$ must be one of $a_0, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // $M_2$ must be one of $a_0, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        //
        // Consider the set of elements $\{a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}\}$.
        // At most $n$ elements can be chosen from this set.
        //
        // Consider the set of elements $\{a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$.
        // At most $n$ elements can be chosen from this set.
        //
        // The median of a class of size $2k+1$ is the $(k+1)$-th element.
        //
        // The total number of elements smaller than $a_{n-1}$ is $n-1$.
        // The total number of elements larger than $a_n$ is $n-1$.
        //
        // Let $M_1$ be the median of $C_1$ and $M_2$ be the median of $C_2$.
        //
        // If $M_1$ and $M_2$ are both $\le a_{n-1}$, then $C_1$ and $C_2$ together must contain at least $k_1+1+k_2+1 = n+1$ elements from $a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$.
        // But there are only $n$ such elements. This is a contradiction.
        // So at least one median must be $> a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // If $M_1$ and $M_2$ are both $\ge a_n$, then $C_1$ and $C_2$ together must contain at least $k_1+1+k_2+1 = n+1$ elements from $a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // But there are only $n$ such elements. This is a contradiction.
        // So at least one median must be $< a_n$.
        //
        // Combining these, one median must be $\le a_{n-1}$ and the other must be $\ge a_n$.
        // (Or one median is $a_{n-1}$ and the other is $a_n$, or one is smaller than $a_{n-1}$ and the other is larger than $a_n$).
        //
        // Let $M_1 \le M_2$.
        // Then $M_1 \le a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 \ge a_n$.
        //
        // This means $M_2 - M_1 \ge a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // Since we found a construction that achieves $a_n - a_{n-1}$, this must be the minimum possible difference.
        //
        // The construction:
        // Class 1: $\{a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{n-2}, a_{n-1}, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}\}$
        // This class has $n-1$ elements from $a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}$ (smaller than $a_{n-1}$),
        // $a_{n-1}$ itself,
        // and $n-1$ elements from $a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ (larger than $a_{n-1}$).
        // Total size: $(n-1) + 1 + (n-1) = 2n-1$. This is an odd size.
        // Its median is $a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // Class 2: $\{a_n\}$
        // This class has size 1, which is odd.
        // Its median is $a_n$.
        //
        // All $2n$ students are assigned. Each class has an odd number of students.
        // The absolute difference is $|a_n - a_{n-1}|$.
        //
        // This logic seems sound and covers all cases.
        //
        // So the answer is $a[n] - a[n-1]$ after sorting.

        long long result = a[n] - a[n - 1];
        std::cout << result << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}

#include <iostream>
